                        Hurley
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d90</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">90</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-07-03T05:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-07-03T05:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-03T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-03T05:00:00-05:00" n="90" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d90">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 P.W./7–345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-03T17:00:00+07:00">July 3, 1945—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 3—11:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1096. Department’s telegram 992, June 20 [<hi rend="italic">26</hi>], 3 p.m. This
                    telegram sent to the Department and repeated to London and New Delhi.</p>
                <p>Regarding the Chinese troops which were reported to have crossed the Thai border
                    near Mong Yawng. The Deputy Chief of Staff, U. S. Army Forces, China
                        Theater,<note n="56" xml:id="d90fn56">Maj. Gen. H. H. Fuller.</note> states
                    that General Wedemeyer will request the Generalissimo to have these Chinese
                    troops withdrawn.</p>
                <p>The only information in the premises received by headquarters is the OSS report
                    referred to in the Department’s telegram.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
